% gen311 (riddles-as-inference, F.): a riddle is an EQUATION solved by inference,
% not a memorized cue->answer. The clue verbs map to constraint predicates that are
% RULES over world knowledge; the answer is the inanimate entity satisfying every
% clue. "no voice, yet I cry ... no eyes, yet I flash in the dark" -> a storm.
% Curated here are the bridging rules + seed property/metaphor facts; autolearn grows
% the FACTS (clue_verb/emits/is_like/inanimate are the teachable layer, not the rules).
clue_verb(cry, cries).
clue_verb(cries, cries).
clue_verb(flash, flashes).
clue_verb(flashes, flashes).
cries($X) :- emits($X, $W), is_like($W, crying).
flashes($X) :- emits($X, $L), is_like($L, flash).
emits(storm, rain).
emits(storm, lightning).
is_like(rain, crying).
is_like(lightning, flash).
inanimate(storm).
% gen311 (U1, riddles-as-inference): "I have A but no B" = depicts(X,A) ∧ ¬contains(X,B).
% The negation is load-bearing: a map DEPICTS cities/mountains/water but does not
% CONTAIN houses/trees/fish, while a real country depicts AND contains them — so the
% ¬contains constraint is what picks the map. Grow depicts/contains via autolearn.
depicts(map, cities).
depicts(map, mountains).
depicts(map, water).
depicts(country, cities).
depicts(country, mountains).
depicts(country, water).
contains(country, houses).
contains(country, trees).
contains(country, fish).
